marked: Studies including resting-state functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI

In the present study, we mapped the number of connections and the strength of resting-state FC between meta-analytically determined hotspots of brain activation observed during successful memory retrieval

The aims of the present study were to test whether FC between these core brain regions (1) can be observed during rest, (2) is altered in aMCI and AD, and (3) is predictive of episodic memory impairment as assessed by standard neuropsychological tests.
23 elderly cognitively healthy controls (HC), 76 subjects with aMCI and 19 AD.
we found higher strength of FC between the right MFG and the PHC to be associated with reduced episodic memory performance in aMCI
There was an association between higher strength of FC in the MFG-PHC connection and lower episodic memory score in the AD group
we included GM volume of the FC ROIs
For the MFG-PHC connection, FC remained a significant predictor of episodic memory in the aMCI and AD groups.
